sticky gobs of oil and grotesque 
portuguese menofwar blown ashore by an east wind have made the 
footing treacherous on some beaches in south florida 
the coast guard hadnt determined the source of the tarlike 
glop washed by strong winds and surf onto beaches around fort 
lauderdale 
its wet and clinging to everything thats floating said 
area resident pauline gerweck tourists are coming out covered 
head to toe this is scandalous 
the jellyfishlike menofwar whose sting can be dangerous to 
the allergic are flopping ashore from the keys to jupiter in palm 
beach county about a 200mile stretch but few stings have been 
reported because bathers are staying out of the water which has 
been stirred by rainshowers and rough seas 
i think with all the warnings people are staying out of the 
water bonnetta kaplan a lifeguard in pompano beach said 
wednesday when something like this happens we load the beach 
with signs 
two weeks ago hundreds of swimmers were stung in south florida 
when swarms of the jellyfish washed up on the beaches 
that coincided with some real nice sunny weather said capt 
bill pallowick of the fort lauderdale beach patrol there are 
probably 10 times more of them out there today but the weather is 
not good 
it was harder for beachgoing tourists to avoid the tar spots 
jim haskell a tourist from newburyport mass said the soles 
of his feet were black with oil after he strolled near anglins 
pier in lauderdalebythesea 
there were some little kids in the surf and they were just 
covered with it haskell said 
coast guard officer pete thiel in fort lauderdale said the 
coast guard twice inspected tankers anchored off the citys coast 
on wednesday but found no evidence of leaks 
huge oil tankers enter and leave port everglades daily and 
frequently anchor off fort lauderdale thiel said tankers sometimes 
pump oily bilge water into the ocean in violation of federal law 
