<TEXT>
the government tried thursday to intimidate 
witnesses who testified for one of manuel noriegas codefendents 
by threatening them with immigration agents who questioned their 
legal status a defense attorney charged 
the agents demanded that three witnesses who testified for luis 
del cid on tuesday turn over all their immigration papers and give 
information about how they obtained passports into the united 
states said samuel burstyn del cids attorney 
burstyn filed a motion late thursday asking us district judge 
william hoeveler to order the government to refrain from contacting 
defense witnesses without their permission 
burstyn told the associated press that he hoped to hear friday 
morning when hoeveler would grant a hearing on his emergency 
motion the us attorneys office had no immediate comment 
earlier thursday defense attorneys accused the government of 
balking at court orders to turn over both secret and nonsecret 
documents to aid the defense in the case against noriega and his 
codefendants 
and a lawyer for convicted drug kingpin carlos lehder rivas 
strongly denied his client will cooperate with the government to 
convict the deposed panamanian leader despite a taped interview 
the imprisoned trafficker gave implicating noriega 
on wednesday hoeveler announced a march 5 trial date for 
noriega and the other defendants after burstyn demanded his 
clients right to a speedy trial 
burstyn said he hoped the date far earlier than the nine 
months to two years most attorneys had anticipated would force 
the government to cease dragging its feet on documents 
there is a desire to stonewall information burstyn said 
its an effort to hermetically seal off the guts and gore of the 
early investigation 
he emphasized he has not yet requested cia or other sensitive 
records only routine matters such as the prior criminal record of 
floyd carlton carceres the former noriega pilot whose testimony 
helped bring about the february 1988 drugtrafficking indictment 
us attorneys office spokeswoman diane cossin refused to 
comment beyond saying defense attorneys should do as instructed 
and not try this case in the media 
one attorney who has unsuccessfully sought secret material is 
michael okane lawyer for accused drug pilot daniel miranda when 
he requested information from a national security agency listening 
post in panama city prosecutors threatened to try him just for 
revealing its existence 
i tend to think that a lot of this case is going to go away 
because i dont think that a lot of the intelligence agencies want 
to reveal things okane said 
he said noriega was a cia asset since at least the 1960s and 
noted the case of cia agent joe fernandez whose indictment in the 
irancontra affair was eventually dropped because the government 
feared the trial would reveal too many secrets 
joe fernandezs case had to be dismissed and joe fernandez 
was a pipsqueak compared to noriega okane said 
the lawyer said that from the reaction of the us attorneys 
office to requests for information he suspected the prosecturs 
were not receiving cooperation from washington agencies 
i dont think anyone is telling them just what the situation 
is he said 
speculation that the government may have the help of testimony 
from convicted medellin cartel trafficker lehder was dismissed by 
lehders attorney jose quinon 
in a prison interview with the west german magazine stern 
recorded in november and broadcast wednesday on nbc news lehder 
said he had paid noriega several million dollars for protection 
lehder also said noriega confiscated drugs and processing 
equipment then sold it to drug dealers in colombia panama and the 
united states 
quinon said thursday that the interview was lehders idea and 
was no indication he planned to cooperate with prosecutors trying 
noriega 
he will be no witness against noriega there is no deal 
theres no cooperation with the government quinon said 
the us attorneys office spokeswoman ms cossin said she 
could not reveal the names of witnesses 
</TEXT>
