<TEXT>
concern about asbestos in schools and public 
buildings may be overstated suggests a group of researchers who 
say there is little data showing that asbestos levels in such 
buildings are a health hazard 
the report by a group of scientists as reported in science 
magazine said that although most of the health concerns from 
asbestos stem from studies involving occupational exposure there 
is no data to show similar risks to the general public exposed to 
airborne asbestos 
surveys of asbestos in schools and public buildings show that 
the mean airborne concentrations are several thousand times lower 
than in workplace environments that existed before asbestos was 
strictly regulated said the study 
asbestos once widely used for insulation and other purposes 
has been shown to cause lung cancer asbestosis a scarring of the 
lung and mesothelioma a cancer of the chest and abdomen the 
federal government has directed that schools inspect for asbestos 
and develop plans to have it removed or enclosed so occupants will 
not be exposed to airborne particles 
the researchers three from the united states one from 
scotland and one from france argue that most of the studies on 
asbestos have involved asbestos miners and other workers routinely 
exposed to the cancercausing materal in the workplace 
an important issue is whether these diseases are also hazards 
to the general population exposed to airborne levels of asbestos in 
schools and other buildings said the researchers 
the findings noted there are different forms of asbestos and 
that each poses different health risks 
the available data said the report do not indicate that 
asbestosassociated malignancies or functional impairment will 
occur as a result of exposure to most airborne concentrations of 
asbestos in buildings 
the scientists said that even when asbestoscontaining materials 
in buildings are damaged the levels of airborne asbestos normally 
found are magnitudes lower than concentrations in the unregulated 
workplace in the past 
airborne asbestos levels found in schools and buildings normally 
are no more than 1 percent of levels considered today to be 
permissible in the workplace by the occupational safety and health 
administration the scientists said 
furthermore said the scientists with few exceptions the type 
of asbestos fiber found predominantly in buildings is chrysotile 
accumulating evidence indicates that this asbestos type is probably 
not associated with the occurrence of mesotheliomas at low levels 
of exposure 
the scientists said the rate of deaths from mesothelioma over 
the past 10 to 20 years has been increasing among males over 65 
years of age that have a past occupational history of exposure to 
asbestos but similar rates among females of all ages have declined 
or remained constant 
these results support the concept that asbestos in buildings 
is not an important risk factor as one would expect increased 
mesotheliomas in both males and females said the study 
the findings were authored by bt mossman of the university of 
vermont college of medicine j bignon a leading french medical 
researcher m corn of johns hopkins university a seaton 
director of the institute of occupational medicine in edinburgh 
scotland and jbl gee of yale university school of medicine 
