<TEXT>
a new congressional study estimates less than 
10 percent of president bushs proposed capital gains tax cut would 
go to occasional investors including those who once in a lifetime 
sell a family farm or business 
more than 81 percent of the benefit would be reaped by those who 
are likely to report capital gains in three or more of every five 
years according to an analysis by the staff of the joint committee 
on taxation 
rep byron l dorgan dnd a house ways and means committee 
member who opposes a capital gains cut said the report explodes 
the myth perpetrated by president bush that his proposal is a tax 
cut for middleincome families and designed to help those who sell 
a farm or business theyve held for 20 years 
mark bloomfield executive director of the american council for 
capital formation a business group that supports a capital gains 
cut said the study does not refute arguments for a reduction 
our point is that there are middleclass people who 
periodically do realize capital gains and the tax system considers 
them rich every year by the way it taxes them bloomfield said 
that is not right 
the new analysis of internal revenue service data found 589 
percent of capital gains recorded in a fiveyear period were 
reported by people who had gains every year more than 81 percent 
of the profits were reported by taxpayers who had gains in at least 
three of the five years 
by contrast 98 percent of the gains were collected by those 
who reported gains in only one of the five years including those 
whose only capital gains were profits from the sale of a home farm 
or business 
among taxpayers who realized gains in the period 1979 through 
1983 a substantial number of taxpayers 437 percent realized 
onetime or nonrecurring gains the committee staff concluded 
however in dollar value the bulk of realizations were 
undertaken by taxpayers who were repeatedly in the market 
the analysis seeks to answer the question of who would actually 
benefit from cutting the tax on capital gains which are profits 
from the sale of stock and other investments 
democrats cite estimates that 80 percent of the benefit would go 
to those with total incomes more than 100000 a year republicans 
say it is misleading to list someone as having an over100000 
income when a person for instance earns 30000 a year but sells 
a family business for a 100000 profit 
bush who will renew his call for a capital gains reduction in 
the budget he sends to congress jan 29 criticized opponents of 
the cut in a speech earlier this month i am sick and tired of 
the demagogues who call this a tax cut for the rich it means jobs 
it means savings and it is good for all americans he said 
the congressional study found people with noncapital gains 
income under 20000 filed 28 percent of the returns on which gains 
were reported but had only 20 percent of the dollar value of the 
gains even the 20 percent figure was distorted the report stated 
because it included people whose taxable incomes were less than 
zero due to a business or farm loss or a tax shelter 
since enactment of the 1986 landmark tax overhaul capital gains 
have been fully taxed at the same rates that apply to other income 
bush wants to exclude as much as 30 percent of capital gains from 
taxation which would mean such profits would be taxed at lower 
rates than apply to wages 
the house over objections of democratic leaders approved a 
reduction last year in the capital gains tax democratic leaders 
blocked a cut in the senate although a majority of senators 
favored it 
</TEXT>
