political veteran tomisaburo hashimoto a powerful 
figure in japans governing party who was convicted in the lockheed 
bribery scandal died today a hospital official said he was 88 
the official at tokyo hospital said hashimoto died of pneumonia 
during the 19641972 administration of late prime minister 
eisaku sato hashimoto served in such key posts as 
secretarygeneral of the governing liberal democratic party 
construction minister and transport minister 
in 1976 while transport minister he was arrested on charges of 
accepting 34000 for promoting sales of aircraft by lockheed corp 
of the united states to a japanese airline 
the tokyo district court later sentenced him to a 2year jail 
term hashimoto who denied the bribery charges took his case to 
the supreme court but the court has not yet issued a ruling 
the lockheed scandal erupted in 1976 when the us aircraft 
maker acknowledged it had bribed japanese officials to influence 
their decisions on plane purchases the scandal was the worst up to 
that time in japans postwar history and caused a split in the 
liberal democrats that took several years to repair 
hashimoto a native of ibaraki prefecture northeast of tokyo 
joined the asahi shimbun a major japanese newspaper in 1927 after 
graduating from the department of politics and economics at waseda 
university 
he quit the newspaper company after world war ii and won his 
first election to the nations lower house of parliament in 1949 
hashimoto returned to the house of representatives 12 times before 
he lost in general elections in 1980 
he served as construction minister from july to december 1960 in 
the late hayato ikedas cabinet 
hashimoto also acted as secretarygeneral in the cabinet of 
former prime minister kakuei tanaka who governed from july 1972 to 
december 1974 tanaka who was also implicated in the lockheed 
scandal is still appealing his case to the supreme court 
there was no immediate word on survivors or funeral arrangements 
