<TEXT>
nine chronic diseases responsible for more than 
half the deaths in the united states are getting only 2 percent of 
the states public health dollars according to new federal health 
research 
the national centers for disease control reported thursday that 
the chronic diseases diseases with long periods of onset or 
suffering accounted for 11 million deaths in 1986 52 percent of 
the deaths nationwide 
the diseases are stroke heart disease diabetes obstructive 
lung disease lung cancer breast cancer cervical cancer 
colorectal cancer and cirrhosis of the liver 
cigarette smoking overweight high blood pressure drinking and 
lack of exercise contribute to some or all of the diseases 
theyre all largely preventable or preventable to some 
extent said dr robert hahn a cdc epidemiologist 
we know what the risk factors are hahn said we know less 
about how you get people to act on them 
the survey of 45 states and the district of columbia found that 
less than 2 percent of state public health expenditures were 
allocated to prevent and control chronic disease the average state 
expenditure was just 66 cents per person per year hahn said 
comparable figures on federal public health spending for chronic 
disease were not available hahn said 
most of the health money from state governments in the united 
states is tied up in medicaid especially with the mounting 
federal deficit in the 1980s said dr robert blendon chairman of 
the department of health policy and management at the harvard 
school of public health 
most public health activities at the state level were paid for 
by federal grants but those grants are now fewer and states are 
left scrambling just to fund medicaid care for their sickest 
citizens blendon said 
prevention of chronic disease became the residual that 
disappeared he said 
its very frustrating we just dont have the early warning 
prevention systems the minimal stuff that anybody who looks 
sensibly at this would want to do blendon said 
the 1986 death toll from the cdcs list of nine chronic diseases 
included 593000 deaths from heart disease 149000 from stroke 
125000 from lung cancer 71000 from obstructive lung disease 
such as emphysema and 55000 from colorectal cancer there were 
40000 breast cancer deaths 37000 from diabetes 26000 from 
cirrhosis and 4500 cervical cancer deaths 
the cdc said death rates from the nine preventable chronic 
diseases were generally lower in the west the highest 1986 death 
rate was in michigan 518 such deaths per 100000 people lowest 
was in hawaii 327 per 100000 
