<TEXT>
a graduate student told a jury he became 
frightened when he realized the worm program he introduced into a 
federal computer network was replicating out of control 
robert t morris speaking publicly for the first time about the 
nov 2 1988 attack that disabled an estimated 6000 computers 
nationwide testified thursday that the worm was an experiment that 
turned into a dismal failure because of a programming error he 
made 
are you proud of yourself his attorney thomas guidoboni 
asked 
no im not said morris 25 who has been suspended by 
cornell university and faces up to five years in prison and a 
250000 fine if convicted of a felony computertampering charge 
i was scared it seemed like the worm was getting out of 
control morris said my purpose was to see if i could write a 
program that would spread as widely as possible my intention was 
that it should not grow the worm spread on the network far faster 
than i expected 
morris testimony was the last in the federal trial closing 
statements are scheduled for monday 
questioned by prosecutor mark rasch morris freely admitted 
designing the worm to break into the internet network which links 
computers at major universities nasa and several military 
facilities 
morris said he gathered passwords from various universities and 
without permission decoded them to make sure the worm would spread 
widely he said he also took steps to make it difficult to detect 
during questioning by guidoboni morris told the jury he 
included mechanisms to limit the worms growth and left out any 
commands that would have caused it to permanently damage existing 
files in the computers it attacked 
he said he wanted to avoid overloading the network so he 
decided on a method to let the worm reenter computers it already 
had infected just once in every seven tries 
morris thought the worm would duplicate a few times a day or 
every few hours but the programming error caused the worm to 
continually reenter each computer 
morris said he unleashed the worm into the internet network 
through computers at the massachusetts institute of technology in 
cambridge mass at about 8 pm on nov 2 1988 
he said he then went out for dinner and when he returned about 
three hours later he noticed cornells own computer was slow to 
respond to commands 
morris said that when he found copies of the worm in the cornell 
system he knew it was spreading and realized it wasnt working 
right 
initially morris said he considered sending out a second worm 
designed to track down and destroy the first worm but morris said 
he decided against that after seeing the unpredictable nature of 
the first worm 
instead he said he called andrew sudduth a friend at harvard 
university and asked him to send a message on an electronic 
bulletin board read mainly by internet users morris said he wanted 
to apologize for unleashing the worm and tell users how to 
eliminate it 
sudduth testified wednesday that it took two days for the 
message to reach the bulletin board because the route he picked was 
backed up 
