<TEXT>
east german communist party factions today 
demanded the partys dissolution and the interim president said 
the prodemocracy opposition should help run the caretaker 
government until elections in may 
several thousand people demonstrated today in the cities of 
leipzig suhl and frankfurt an der oder to press for demands that 
included better education and higher wages the official news 
agency adn said 
the actions came as the bonn government increasingly disturbed 
by the flow of east germans resettling in the west blamed the 
communists for the countrys woes and insisted on eventual german 
unity as the solution 
the developments indicate how difficult east germanys road to 
reform has been since a prodemocracy revolution ousted hardline 
communist leader erich honecker on oct 18 opened the berlin wall 
and set up a coalition government that is trying to lead the 
country until democratic elections are held in may 
interim president manfred gerlach a noncommunist said the 
opposition could take over some of the 16 cabinet seats held by the 
communists or the three christian democratic seats the christian 
democrats have threatened to pull out of the shaky 27member 
coalition goverment of communists and parties that have 
traditionally allied with them 
in a statement released today in east berlin several communist 
party movements demanded the partys uncompromising dissolution 
under public control 
the party whose membership has plunged from 23 million to 14 
million in six months is wracked by internal squabbles 
the delegates to the extraordinary party congress held in 
december should again be summoned to agree to the dissolution 
said the statement carried by adn 
it did not say how many party members supported it but it 
listed seven communist factions 
more than 1800 east germans continue to resettle in west 
germany each day threatening the bonn governments ability to 
feed house and give jobs to the newcomers 
reflecting concern over the instability in east germany west 
german chancellor helmut kohls chief of staff on thursday demanded 
a clear commitment to german unity from the east berlin leadership 
the official rudolf seiters said the communists were 
guilty of a lack of willingness to introduce fundamental 
political and economic reforms 
with every day that passes the chances of a lasting recovery 
of the economy in the gdr east germany worsen seiters said 
this is due to the fact that the highly qualified manpower 
which has left is urgently needed within its own country the last 
thing which the gdr can now afford is further bloodletting 
the more than 340000 east germans who have resettled in west 
germany are mostly young skilled workers 
strikes and demonstrations have kept up the pressure on the 
communist premier hans modrows government while boosting the 
leverage of opposition forces 
in order to join a caretaker government the opposition has 
demanded participation in overseeing a dismantling of the dreaded 
secret police and a right to speak in parliament negotiators 
quickly approved resolutions backing both demands 
 
modrow appealed to his coalition partners to hold the government 
together until the nations first free elections set for may 
spokesman wolfgang meyer said 
in bonn seiters spelled out west germanys vision of the next 
steps toward a united germany 
he told lawmakers that shortly after the may elections bonn 
will seek a treaty arrangement with east berlin 
the treaty arrangement is the first step toward confederative 
structures which are to lead to a federal structure in germany 
seiters said emphasizing that kohl intends to keep pushing for 
german unity 
this view of unity must be made very clear in the treaty 
that is to be worked out seiters said we hope that a freely 
elected parliament in the german democratic republic will 
strengthen such a view for the solution of the german question and 
thus the goal of german national unity 
modrow himself first called for closer treaty ties although the 
communist premier said he was insisting on an independent east 
german state 
the east german social democrats considered the most likely to 
head the government after the may elections have said they favor 
german unity and want to start talks on the issue as soon as 
possible following the vote 
