<TEXT>
premier li peng on friday signed new regulations 
governing foreign journalists in china the official xinhua news 
agency said but it did not disclose their contents 
foreign journalists were under tight restrictions in beijing 
during nearly eight months of martial law that ended jan 11 the 
new regulations are expected to reimpose at least some of those 
restrictions 
the state council chinas cabinet approved them on the same 
day that martial law ended xinhua said the regulations were 
necessary to supervise the activities of foreign journalists and 
resident foreign news organizations 
the foreign ministry has refused to divulge their contents and 
xinhua did not say if they take effect with lis signing 
under martial law foreign journalists were banned from 
conducting interviews without army approval all interview requests 
had to be submitted to the city government and weeks often passed 
before a response was made usually negative 
the government expelled two foreign reporters based in beijing 
following its june 34 army crackdown on prodemocracy protesters 
and half a dozen visiting journalists police surveillance of 
journalists including audible telephone bugs increased sharply 
during the summer but appears to have relaxed recently 
information continues to be hard to get however because many 
chinese officials consider it politically risky to grant interviews 
the beijing city government meanwhile approved a regulation 
forbidding books magazines and audio or videotapes that violate 
the fundamental principles of the constitution are pornographic 
superstititious or contain other evils 
it reiterated that all book magazine newspaper and tape 
sellers must be officially licensed a requirement that has been 
widely ignored in the past 
authorities nationwide have conducted an intensive campaign 
since june against pornographic and politically suspect materials 
they have raided book stalls burned tens of thousands of books and 
magazines and shut down many book distributors and several 
publishing companies 
