<TEXT>
frank h king whose 38 years with the 
associated press included a 7000mile odyssey across siberia while 
covering the russian revolution died friday he was 96 
king died at an oakland convalescent and senior home 
he was the first american reporter to describe in eyewitness 
accounts life in revolutionary russia his exclusive reports were 
widely read in america and europe 
after his epic journey king covered washington then was 
assigned to london for 17 years where he was chief of bureau he 
was dallas bureau chief and general executive for the southwest 
before retiring on dec 31 1958 
king a native of excelsior springs mo and a graduate of the 
university of missouri school of journalism was hired as an ap 
stringer in columbia mo he joined the st louis postdispatch 
but his 1750 weekly pay was not enough to hold him when he got a 
chance to join the englishlanguage japan advertiser in tokyo 
with russia in revolution the united states britain france 
and japan sent expeditionary forces to vladivostok in 1918 the ap 
and the japan advertiser together hired king to cover the turmoil 
at one point he was commended by the american command for 
helping to rescue women and children besieged by revolutionaries in 
the vladivostok railway station 
finally admiral alexander kolchak the white russian leader 
was seized and executed by the bolsheviks and resistance collapsed 
in the spring of 1920 the allies pulled out 
as japanese soldiers took to shooting at almost anything that 
moved king decided it was healthier to return to tokyo other than 
by the direct route instead he made his way down the coast to 
china and peking 
the situation changed kings instinct told him to go west he 
put a small kit together and headed across mongolia siberia and 
russia where no one in the western world had any idea what was 
going on 
king was strictly on his own traveling on anything available 
he walked rode in a pony cart a river steamer and on the 
transsiberian railway 
always on the move he went through the great wall and across 
the gobi desert he filed stories never knowing until long after 
whether the copy arrived 
moscow authorities finally interned him in an old expropriated 
czarist mansion while they debated what to do with him 
king was rescued by john reed an american radical and darling 
of the leninists the authorities decided the best solution was to 
send king across the border into finland from there he made his 
way to london 
he is survived by his wife olga and son fhh king a 
college professor in new mexico funeral arrangements were pending 
