<TEXT>
it is not necessary to define when human 
life begins to impose criminal penalties for killing a fetus the 
minnesota supreme court ruled friday 
the court in upholding minnesotas 1986 fetal homicide 
statutes said the laws do not raise the issue of when life as a 
human person begins or ends the state must prove only that the 
implanted embryo or the fetus in the mothers womb was living that 
it had life and that it has life no longer 
the justices in a 43 decision held that the fetal homicide 
statutes are constitutional even though they dont distinguish 
between viable and nonviable fetuses 
the defendant who assaults a pregnant woman causing the death 
of the fetus she is carrying destroys the fetus without the consent 
of the woman the court said this is not the same as the woman 
who elects to have her pregnancy terminated by one legally 
authorized to perform the act 
the us supreme courts landmark 1973 ruling that legalized 
abortion protects the womans right of choice it does not 
protect much less confer on an assailant a thirdparty unilateral 
right to destroy the fetus the minnesota justices said 
the opinion was issued in the case of sean patrick merrill of 
rochester who has been charged with two counts each of first and 
seconddegree murder in the november 1988 shooting deaths of 
22yearold gail anderson and her 4weekold embryo 
rochester attorney kevin lund merrills lawyer said a decision 
on whether to appeal further is expected within about a week 
olmsted county district judge o russell olson had denied 
merrills motion to dismiss the charges relating to the embryo but 
asked for a ruling on the constitutionality of the 1986 fetal 
homicide statutes 
olson said minnesotas statutes represent the most sweeping 
legislative attempt in the country to criminalize actions of third 
parties which harm fetuses and embryos 
in rejecting merrills claim that the statutes were fatally 
vague because they dont define the phrase causes the death of 
an unborn child the court split 43 with associate justice 
glenn kelley breaking from the majority justices rosalie wahl and 
am sandy keith dissented from the entire majority opinion 
writing for the dissent kelley said that without a statutory 
definition the phrase causes the death of an unborn child is 
burdened with ambiguity which invites arbitrary and 
discriminatory enforcement 
lund said he found it a a moral victory that three of the 
seven justices found the death of unborn child phrasing 
ambiguous unfortunately moral victories dont count in a 
court of law he said 
olmsted county attorney ray schmitz who defended the statutes 
before the supreme court said the justices were careful to 
separate the fetal homicide issue from abortion 
our argument was that the constitutionally protected 
relationship between mother and fetus is entirely different than 
actions of a third party and that is essentially what the court 
said he said 
the challenged statutes impose criminal penalties for murder 
of an unborn child in the first and second degrees the penalties 
of life imprisonment for conviction on a firstdegree charge and up 
to 40 years on a seconddegree charge are the same as for murder 
the statutes define unborn child as the offspring of a 
human being conceived but not yet born 
the court said it appeared merrill was claiming that because 
the statutes do not distinguish between viable and nonviable 
fetuses he was exposed to conviction as a murderer of an unborn 
child during the first trimester of pregnancy on the other hand a 
woman who obtains a legal abortion under roe vs wade and the 
doctor who performs it are not murderers 
the justices said however that the focus of the roe vs wade 
decision was on protecting a pregnant woman from governmental 
interference or compulsion 
</TEXT>
