system bellowing get out of our motherland why dont you 
respect our country 
many of japans estimated 820 ultrarightist groups spend their 
time driving along city streets in darkpainted trucks blaring 
martial music or in harassing perceived opponents like nakajima 
who also heads the united church of christ japans largest 
protestant denomination 
but some rightist groups in their quest to protect their vision 
of japanese spiritual and political purity have been implicated in 
violent attacks such as the shooting thursday of nagasaki mayor 
hitoshi motoshima 
motoshima who was seriously wounded received death threats 
after saying that the late emperor hirohito shared responsibility 
for japans involvement in world war ii the leader of a rightist 
group kazumi tajiri has confessed to the shooting police said 
although the number of ultraright organizations has grown in 
recent years police estimate the membership to be about 120000 
the same as a decade ago their ideas are much the same too 
reverence for the emperor and a pure japan anticommunism 
opposition to leftist unions and liberal opinion and a willingness 
to use violence that recalls the early 20th century when 
assassination was a political tool in japan 
the groups have little public support and often instill more 
fear than respect but their highprofile activities have made 
their impact considerable 
fear of rightist reprisals along with respect for the imperial 
family has kept the question of hirohitos wartime responsibility 
a largely taboo subject attacks on newspaper offices attributed to 
rightists such as the murder of a reporter for the liberal asahi 
shimbun in 1987 have had a chilling psychological effect on news 
reporting 
there should be many opinions allowed about the emperors war 
responsibility said former nagasaki vice mayor soichi urabe 
although many people are criticizing the violence of the attack 
on mayor motoshima most people still arent considering the more 
basic issue 
police say they monitor the rightist groups but in most cases 
have no reason to take action because of the constitutional 
guarantee of freedom of expression 
however some rightists have been arrested for violating an 
antinoise law imposed in 1988 to protect parliament and foreign 
