<TEXT>
myles f horton a major influence on a 
generation of civil rights leaders who founded a school that led 
the movement to franchise blacks died friday of cancer he was 84 
horton a selfdescribed radical hillbilly saw literacy as 
a key to breaking racial barriers and envisioned a new south long 
before others thought it possible 
in 1932 horton helped found the highlander folk school near 
chattanooga often called the backbone of the civil rights 
movement the school educated impoverished southern workers labor 
union leaders and civil rights activists 
martin luther king jr ralph abernathy eleanor roosevelt rosa 
parks john l lewis and andrew young were influenced by horton and 
supported his endeavors 
myles horton was one of those suffering servants who had a 
vision of justice in the south long before it was deemed 
possible young said earlier this week 
john gaventa director of the highlander research and education 
center as the school is now called said horton died surrounded by 
friends and family at his home on the schools campus 20 miles 
east of knoxville tenn 
horton had been fighting cancer for 2 years and last month was 
diagnosed with an inoperable brain tumor he slipped into a deep 
coma jan 13 
a group of highlander associates started the first citizenship 
school in the sea islands off south carolina the forerunner of 
other schools that taught poor blacks to read so they could pass 
literacy tests and vote 
in the 1930s highlander was a training school for the congress 
of industrial organizations or the cio and supported coal miners 
farmers and textile workers organize unions in the depression era 
highlander was one of the few places in the south where blacks 
and whites could meet and discuss social change it was closely 
allied with the southern christian leadership conference and martin 
luther king 
mrs roosevelt defended highlander when mccarthyites attacked 
the school in the 1950s as a training center and safe haven for 
communists 
the state of tennessee shut down highlander in 1959 saying 
interracial gatherings and alleged liquor sales at the school 
violated the schools charter highlander was auctioned in 1961 
but started again a decade later 
horton received a lifetime achievement award from the american 
civil liberties union of tennessee in 1989 the martin luther king 
jr award from the fellowship of reconciliation a religious group 
the rothko chapel award for commitment to truth and freedom in 
1986 and the literacy education award from the international 
council of adult education in paris in 1982 among other honors 
the son of a sharecropper horton was born july 9 1905 in 
savannah tenn he attended cumberland university in tennessee 
union theological seminary in new york and then the university of 
