aid to panama is being delayed up to 45 days 
in some cases because of inappropriate intrusions by congress 
into administration affairs attorney general dick thornburgh said 
friday 
thornburgh addressing an annual meeting of the federalist 
society said the lawmakers are increasingly attempting to 
micromanage the executive branch on matters such as foreign 
affairs routine executive branch operations and even internal 
deliberations 
even today the presidents flexibility to act with dispatch 
to help our friends in panama is hampered and delayed by 
congressional caveats the attorney general said 
they were impetuously passed to stop any foreign aid or 
military support or tariff relief from ever going to general 
manuel noriega now noriega is in a miami jail because of prompt 
executive action but these regs are still on the books 
blocking help to panama in some cases for 45 days 
such provisions constitute clearly inappropriate intrusions by 
congress into executive branch management thornburgh said 
i have grave doubts that the power of the purse was ever 
intended to include the power to define our foreign relations 
and to require that congress be notified of all covert activities 
within 48 hours even if doing so could threaten american lives 
said the attorney general 
he also expressed concern about congress growing penchant for 
delegating executive power to persons not controlled by the 
president and cited the independent counsel act as an example 
i broach this subject briefly not to impugn any past or 
present independent counsel but to point out forthrightly 
present difficulties and potential dangers that arise even from 
the best of intentions when the separation of powers is ignored 
or as in this case is legislatively gotten round he said 
todays overstepping by the legislative branch does not yet 
threaten individual liberty thornburgh said but it does 
unnecessarily challenge this administrations commitment to a less 
adversarial relationship between the coequal branches of 
government 
the federalist society is named after the federalist papers in 
which alexander hamilton james madison and john jay urged adoption 
of the constitution it was founded in 1981 by three yale and 
university of chicago law students to counter what they saw as a 
liberal bias on law school campuses 
