of illinois introduced his own proposal for preventing use of 
surplus social security taxes to reduce the federal deficit he 
said that unlike moynihans proposal it would protect retirees 
without playing taxcut politics with the social security 
system 
porters plan which is being promoted by house republican whip 
newt gingrich of georgia would return the surplus proportionately 
to workers whose taxes created it they would not receive tax cuts 
or refunds however instead the money would go into a kind of 
individual retirement account and each workers claim on future 
social security benefits would drop as the individual account 
builds 
over a period of 50 years or so porter estimated social 
security gradually would become a private retirement system that 
would prevent congress from spending social security surpluses 
boost national savings and give workers the potential for higher 
retirement benefits than are available under the present system 
porter said 
the white house jumped on moynihans proposal and the 
reemergence of sen ernest f hollings longtime proposal for a 5 
percent valueadded tax a national sales levy as evidence that 
democrats plan to seek a tax increase 
hollings dsc aims to replace revenues lost by the social 
security tax cut and bushs own proposal to lower the tax on 
capital gains 
mitchell said friday hes against hollings tax proposal saying 
that would add to the regressivity of the tax system 
but at the same time he voiced qualms about the impact that 
moynihans proposal would have on the budget deficit 
the concern which has been expressed about it by responsible 
economists is a concern which i share he said i will 
await those studies and the opportunity to discuss the matter 
personally with senator moynihan 
i must say that his suggestion has dramatized and focused 
attention on the increasing inequity and regressive nature of the 
american tax system mitchell said 
he said it demostratees that taxes on the wealthiest people 
have been systematically and dramatically reduced in the past 
decade while taxes for the middleclass have actually risen in 
the aggregate 
