president bush called on congress to approve 
clean air legislation friday but cautioned he will veto any bill 
that is substantially more expensive than the proposal he sent to 
capitol hill last summer 
i will only sign legislation that balances environmental and 
economic progress said the president in a letter to sen bob 
dole rkan the senate minority leader 
bush noting that the senate is planning next week to begin 
floor action on a tough air pollution control bill said the 
proposal is twice as costly as the administration proposal and the 
one under consideration in the house 
the cost to industry of toughening the nations air pollution 
controls is expected to be a major subject of debate as the 
legislation moves forward in congress in the coming months 
senate democrats have said in recent days that their bill is not 
substantially higher in cost from the bush proposal but the 
president in his letter to dole said administration estimates put 
its price tag at more than 40 billion a year compared to 19 
billion for the administration proposal 
at the same time maintained the president the senate bill 
provides little incremental environmental benefit over house 
and administration versions 
environmentalists have maintained the senate bill is much 
stronger and should be enacted 
the presidents letter was made public by dole several hours 
after senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine called for 
quick senate action on clean air legislation calling it a high 
priority for me and for the president 
mitchell made no reference to bushs letter 
he said he anticipated a vigorous floor debate on the 
legislation over the next few weeks mitchell said that if clean 
air legislation is not enacted this year the countrys leadership 
in environmental issues will be called into question worldwide 
clean air bills in both the senate and house call for a 10 
million ton reduction in acid rain pollutants tighter auto 
emission standards and a requirement that a broad range of 
industrial plants and businesses install best available 
technology to capture toxic chemical releases 
the senate bill passed by the environment and public works 
committee last november however includes several second stage 
provisions that the administration and most of industry oppose as 
being too costly 
one provision would require automakers to meet a second round of 
emission curbs beginning in the year 2003 while another would 
require industry to comply with a healthbased standard on toxic 
chemical releases not related to what emission control equipment 
might be available 
supporters of the legislation have argued that the tougher bill 
would not be sustantially more expensive and that industry and 
administration cost estimates are exaggerated 
in his letter to dole the president outlined some provisions a 
bill must have for him to sign it into law these include that it 
contain no national electricity tax to help pay for acid rain curbs 
at the dirtiest electric utilities that a bill achieve overall 
pollution reduction levels he outlined in his proposal and that 
the controls not exceed his administration bill cost estimates by 
more than 10 percent 
in a related development the american lung association said 
friday that the tougher senate clean air bill with its stronger 
auto emissions curbs are needed to reduce air pollution to healthy 
levels 
the group releasing two studies on the effects of dirty air on 
health costs said current health costs stemming from air pollution 
is estimated to be 40 billion to 50 billion a year with about 
half of that coming from auto emissions 
five years ago the highrange estimate was 40 billion a 
year today 40 billion has become the best estimate for midrange 
of the health costs said fran dumelle director of government 
relations for the association 
</TEXT>
