<TEXT>
a federal appeals court friday rejected a 
lawsuit contending the governments fuel economy standards for new 
cars endanger motorists by encouraging automakers to build less 
crashworthy vehicles 
a threejudge panel of the us circuit court of appeals for the 
district of columbia ruled that the national highway traffic safety 
administration regulations were reasonable 
the standards were challenged by the competitive enterprise 
institute an organization supported by foundations and industries 
that favor a nongovernment approach to regulatory issues said 
sam kazman the groups general counsel 
also supporting the suit was consumer alert a 6000member 
group that wants expanded consumer choice in the marketplace 
kazman said 
the suit charged that the governments corporate average fuel 
economy standards for the 1987 through 1989 model years increased 
the number of highway deaths as manufacturers downsized cars to 
reduce their weight and boost gasoline mileage 
the standards required that each automakers fleet of cars 
average 26 miles per gallon for vehicles sold in the 1987 and 1988 
model years and 265 mpg for 1989 if some models fall short of the 
standard others must exceed it so the overall fleet average meets 
the standard 
transportation secretary samuel skinner boosted the 1990 
standard to 275 mpg prompting a separate competitive enterprise 
institute suit that is still pending kazman said 
even tougher standards would be required under bills before 
congress to renew the clean air act a senate environmental panel 
last fall voted to require an average fuel economy standard of 33 
mpg by 1996 and 40 mpg by 2000 
automakers are fighting the proposal which they say would force 
them to discontinue all but their smallest models while consumers 
are demanding bigger more powerful cars 
at least six other bills to boost the fuel economy standards are 
pending 
the suit accused the government of ignoring the threat to safety 
posed by fuel economy standards but the court ruled that the 
agency met its legal obligation to consider the issue kazman said 
he voiced disappointment with the ruling but said it cleared the 
way for action on the second suit 
here we have a safety agency refusing to admit that one of its 
major programs kills people he said in our view the evidence 
is pretty clear that nhtsa not only ignored the safety issue but 
in fact lied about it given the even more disastrous effects 
of the 1990 standard on auto safety were hopeful of a more 
favorable outcome in that litigation 
tim hurd spokesman for the agency said were pleased that 
the court found in our favor were waiting for their judgment on 
the other half of the suit he said he was referring to another 
challenge of the fuel economy standards on environmental grounds 
</TEXT>
