<TEXT>
bulgarias leaders on friday faced a wave 
of labor unrest as the ruling communists headed toward an 
extraordinary party congress likely to approve introduction of 
multiparty democracy and other major reforms 
the state news agency bta said friday more than 100 labor 
conflicts were registered by newly formed independent trade unions 
from dec 25 to jan 10 
the labor unrest surged into the open after bulgarias 
ironfisted communist leader todor zhivkov was deposed on nov 10 
in the reforms that swept eastern europe 
the jan 30 party congress will be the first since his ouster 
zhivkov who has aready been charged with malfeasance in office 
abuse of power and other crimes was accused in a newspaper article 
friday of having been a nazi intelligence agent in wartime bulgaria 
the allegations came in an article in the newspaper otechestven 
front which said zhivov worked out of a sofia villa in 1941 
no further details were available on zhivkovs purported 
intelligence role 
bulgarian king boris iii sided with adolf hitlers nazi germany 
in 1941 and bulgarian troops occupied parts of yugoslavia and 
greece 
zhivkov himself had leveled charges of nazi collaboration 
against the family of his chief critic reformist chudomir 
alexandrov when he kicked alexandrov off the politburo in 1988 
bta reported friday that the main strike demands included 
disclosure of company financial and technical status a cutback in 
bureaucracy dismissal of discredited managers better supply of 
raw materials and equipment and improved working conditions and 
safety 
the communists have conceded it will take years to overcome the 
nations deep economic crisis 
in a separate draft declaration to be presented at the party 
congress this month the party calls for a marketoriented economy 
it says the party favors development of a whole variety of forms 
of social ownership but does not spell out private enterprise 
documents asserting party willingness to adopt farreaching 
reforms were seen as an attempt by the communists now under 
pressure from opposition groups and radical changes elsewhere in 
the bloc to cling to power 
the party congress is set to adopt a statute that drops the 
marxistleninist label and the principle of democratic 
centralism in favor of political pluralism 
this week the communistdominated parliament abolished the 
partys guaranteed monopoly on political power thus officially 
ending more than four decades of authoritarian oneparty rule 
talks with the opposition on powersharing and democratization 
were suspended thursday because of the communist leaderships 
apparent unwillingness to provide the opposition with a voice in 
the nations radio and television 
the union of democratic forces the umbrella organization of all 
major opposition groups reaffirmed its right to criticize the 
communists in a statement read by spokesman ruben vodenicharov on 
state tv friday night 
the exercise of power by a single party means that this one 
party must be taken to account vodenicharov said 
a draft declaration to be advanced at the party congress 
carried by bta said the bulgarian communist party must be 
destalinized and established as a new type of contemporary marxist 
party it stresses the need for a radical restructuring of party 
governing bodies the ruling politburo and the policysetting 
central committee 
the political system of democratic socialism implies a 
multiparty system parliamentary democracy separation of 
legislative executive and judiciary powers guaranteed 
freedoms and autonomy of science and education it said 
the draft proposes that all party officers be elected by secret 
ballot and serve only two terms but did not specify their duration 
it calls for a supreme party council to replace the central 
committee a central control and auditing commission and a central 
commission on party ethics 
it also sets out a format for a chairmanship that would be the 
apparent successor to the politburo 
according to the declaration text quoted by bta the communist 
party is willing to recognize religious and some ethnic rights of 
the minority turks and other bulgarian moslems 
