<TEXT>
a jury began deliberating friday on whether 
two former cincinnati bell telephone co installers defamed the 
company and two of its managers by accusing them of engaging in 
illegal telephone wiretapping 
the hamilton county common pleas court jury deliberated less 
than three hours before judge fred j cartolano sent them home for 
the weekend with instructions not to discuss the case with anyone 
cartolano earlier had directed the eight jurors in the civil 
trial to focus on whether statements by former employees leonard 
gates and robert draise harmed the company its parent cincinnati 
bell inc and phone company managers peter gabor and james west 
the jury must also decide whether gates and draise were 
negligent or demonstrated malice in making the statements as 
cincinnati bell gabor and west allege 
we want your common sense cartolano told the jurors 
the jury which has been hearing the case since nov 20 began 
deliberating friday afternoon since it is a civil case only six 
of the eight jurors need agree on any issue for a ruling 
cartolano on wednesday dismissed the defamation lawsuit that 
gates and draise filed against cincinnati bell leaving the jury to 
decide only the original lawsuit the company filed against the two 
former installers 
the plaintiffs sued demanding 2 million each from gates and 
draise but cartolano instructed the jurors that they must 
determine amounts to be awarded the exception is punitive damages 
which cartolano said he would determine if the jury decided to 
award them 
gates and draise accused their former employer of illegal 
wiretapping of customers including business leaders and federal 
judges cincinnati bell and its managers say the accusations are 
lies and that the company never knew of or authorized illegal 
wiretaps only federal judges may authorize installation of 
electronic listening devices 
cincinnati bell says gates and draise were out to get the 
company because it fired draise in 1979 and gates in 1986 but 
gates and draise say the company is trying to cover up its alleged 
involvement 
you have the ability to send bell and other companies a 
message were not going to stand for it draise told the jury 
he and gates are serving as their own lawyers 
cincinnati bell attorney arnold morelli told the jury that gates 
and draise should not be believed because they changed their 
stories contended they could not remember dates and other details 
of wiretaps and would not take polygraph tests morelli noted that 
gabor and west voluntarily submitted to polygraph tests 
gates and draise say they installed at least 1200 illegal phone 
wiretaps from 1972 to 1984 at the direction of gabor and west or 
cincinnati police intelligence squad members 
morelli said gates changed his story about whether gabor or west 
ordered gates to install a wiretap on thenpresident fords phone 
during fords 1975 visit to cincinnati 
