<TEXT>
general motors corp the worlds largest 
automaker may suffer from a developmental warp a systemic 
imbalance between hightech manufacturing processes and human 
capacity to use them well 
the problem is correctable says a professor who had spent three 
decades analyzing corporate structures but it will require a 
specialist a fiveyear projecttype ceo with years of 
experience to replace roger smith 
smith who will retire this year as chief executive officer 
initiated a 40 billionprogram to modernize production facilities 
in an effort to bring down costs and raise efficiency but gm 
efficiency remains low 
the reason says eugene jennings professor emeritus at michigan 
state university and a confidential adviser to corporate chairmen 
is that gm failed to develop the human organization to work with 
the technology 
specifically the new manufacturing processes were ahead of 
the available experience and knowledge of how to achieve optimal 
efficiency with compatible synchronized human organizations 
in short technology was developed beyond immediate human 
usefulness a familiar problem to anyone who owns a telephone that 
can do a dozen tricks if only they were needed or a personal 
computer that defies understanding 
says jennings gm has too many staff personnel compared to 
line too many overseeing plant people compared to handson types 
at least three too many reporting levels too many committees too 
many parts divisions with uncompetitive costs 
gm fixed costs are too high relative to variable costs and 
its general and administrative costs average several times higher 
per revenue dollar than the leanest competitition 
the statistical evidence is devastatingly clear he says 
observing that gms market share has dropped from 48 percent in 
1980 to 35 percent in 1989 and seems to be headed lower 
harbour amp associates of ann arbor mich estimates that 15 of 
the 16 least efficient plants in north america are gm and among 
the companys least efficient plants are several of their newest 
although estimates vary average profit per vehicle assembled in 
north america recently has been about 50 for gm more than 600 
for ford motor co and more than 1000 for some of the 
transplants or foreign factories on us soil 
in jennings view roger smith deserves credit for having 
tremendous vision in devising his plan to push technology far 
beyond its thenexisting level early in the 1980s 
it was a dream elegant in its conceptualization he says 
but it went so far so fast it surpassed the human capability to 
implement it quality improved but costs didnt fall the 
human aspect was a failure 
in retrospect he believes smith carried the program as far as 
any one person could and he states that no person is sufficiently 
skilled to take on such a 10year stint jennings says a 
secondstage leader should have been named 
what is needed now says jennings is a chairman with a clear 
assignement to develop the human organization that will bring down 
costs 
in his view the gm costreduction program now under way is a 
good start but it must be combined with a resizing of the 
entire company resizing is a euphemism for shrinking the company 
to an efficient level 
how much shrinkage jennings declines to estimate but john 
hammond of jd power and associates an automotive industry 
analyst has mentioned a decline to 29 percent of market share 
before stability and full efficiency are achieved 
jennings believes gm which always has promoted from within 
might have to go outside the company to find the individual suited 
for the challenge 
this idea may have had merit in an oligopolistic market where 
gm could dictate its terms says jennings good ideas are too 
rare to be the exclusive province of insiders 
whoever is chosen says jennings has an opportunity to make gm 
the best managed and lowest cost producer assuming he can mesh 
human and technological elements 
many things are in place for gm to take off he said it 
has tremendous opportunities 
</TEXT>
