matured 
he couldnt accept her as the big fat adult self he could 
never accept that the childhood potential that she showed wasnt 
there now he never helped her to accept reality she was so 
addicted to the love that he once gave her she would seek it from 
anyone she could get it from 
campion grew up in wellington and originally preferred painting 
and plays to film but she learned quickly how to think visually 
admiring women in love performance and other films 
i was aware at an early age how much i loved daydreaming and 
storymaking how potent that was for me i think of filmmaking as 
play its work but i think its play too 
i had a fairly gentle but fairly fast introduction to 
filmmaking but i didnt want to make a feature i wasnt ambitious 
in that way 
she obtained a diploma in anthropology before attending the 
australian film and television school where she directed three 
short films peel passionless moments and a girls own 
story 
her breakthrough came in 1986 at the cannes film festival when 
peel won the palme dor for best short film that same year 
campion developed the storyline for sweetie 
i approached gerry lee and said lets do it together i 
was very worried who was going to be sweetie i felt that 
sweetie needed to be childlike believeable she had to make 
almost anything sound real 
on film the humor is dry ironic matching campions own tight 
smile and clipped accent on the set the laughter was loud and 
jolly reflected by the directors amused mischievous eyes 
we needed an atmosphere that was going to support her lemon 
being such a big character the filmmaker said we had a very 
jolly wild atmosphere she would sing songs at the top of her 
voice and all of us would just carry on we all got a bit nutty at 
times 
the film isnt about sweetie to me its about love and 
delusion and reality she seemed to be the catalyst for a lot of 
these frustrations im not interested in nutty fat girls per se 
im interested in extremes in love and friendship 
