<DOCNO> AP900119-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mk pete peterson trusted his stockbroker 
he says that was his mistake 
the 70yearold retired corporate executive claims that in april 
1987 on his brokers advice he entered into a series of 
complicated transactions that depended on a stock price rising it 
didnt 
the october 87 market crash left peterson with 800000 in 
losses from speculative trades in sophisticated securities with 
fancy names like naked puts and margin calls now the 
dallas millionaire wants his money back 
peterson has taken his case to arbitration the outofcourt 
forum where wall street firms require customers to resolve disputes 
with brokers 
but like many disgruntled investors whose savings are squandered 
through naivete bad judgment or broker incompetence peterson 
contends he cannot get a fair hearing because the arbitration 
system favors the industry 
my lifes about over but ive got one more battle to fight and 
im going to win it said peterson who claims the case has cost 
him about 2 million in trading losses taxes legal fees and other 
expenses about half his net worth 
arbitration has come under increased scrutiny since the supreme 
court last may upheld the constitutionality of contracts that 
require brokerage customers to settle grievances before a hearing 
panel rather than in court 
opponents claim arbitration is biased because it is run by the 
nations stock exchanges and other selfregulatory bodies and 
because panels contain an industry representative proponents say 
it is quicker and faster than litigation and investors do just as 
well in recovering losses 
the securities and exchange commission last year approved 
reforms designed to remove secrecy surrounding the process and ease 
what advocates of arbitration say is an unfounded image of 
anticustomer bias 
arbitrators are deciding the case not some board of directors 
of a stock exchange said theodore a krebsbach director of 
litigation for the wall street firm shearson lehman hutton inc 
its a perception thing not a reality 
unlike litigation arbitration panels make decisions based on 
information presented without complex rules of evidence 
arbitrators do not have to explain decisions and appeals are 
limited panels usually consist of one securities industry 
representative and two arbitrators representing the public 
the worst thing is having a cadre of retired brokers and 
managers people who depended on the industry for ideas and money 
for years sitting in judgment on people who have been ripped off 
by brokers said robert dyer an orlando fla lawyer who 
handles securities arbitration cases 
because of the key supreme court ruling and the bull market 
followed by huge investor losses in the crash arbitration claims 
have surged a total of 6101 cases was filed in 1988 vs 830 in 
1980 
industry figures show investors won 51 percent of the 3731 
cases decided in 198688 of 102 rulings in a threemonth period 
last year victorious plaintiffs recovered about half of the losses 
they claimed according to a study by securities arbitration 
commentator a maplewood nj newsletter 
but if prearbitration settlements are included industry 
officials estimate about 75 percent of grievances result in some 
monetary award high by legal standards 
while customers such as peterson have resources to fight others 
are not as fortunate a divorced new jersey teacher who lost 
100000 in the crash claimed that trading by her shearson broker 
was irresponsible and unsuitable she sought 35744184 in losses 
and damages she got nothing 
others do well by the process a divorced los angeles mother 
recently won 403000 in a case alleging inappropriate investments 
by her painewebber inc broker in a rare punitive damage award 
arbitrators also ordered the firm to pay her 100000 and the 
broker to pay 50000 
but because arbitration panels do not have to issue written 
opinions it is difficult to determine the basis for decisions 
prior to last may the selfregulatory groups were not even 
required to disclose arbitration awards 
the new york stock exchange and national association of 
securities dealers handle about 90 percent of the nations 
arbitrations with the rest occurring at smaller exchanges 
brokerages own and control the selfregulatory groups 
partly because of the bias perception the securities industry 
conference on arbitration last year required that customer 
contracts highlight arbitration clauses formerly buried in fine 
print exchanges also limited independent arbitrators ties to wall 
street 
but lawyers want more choice in deciding who sits on arbitration 
panels a larger pool of arbitrators to choose from mandatory 
written opinions and the right to substitute an independent 
arbitrator for the industry panelist 
i want someone who is more representative of my client than 
someone who is more representative of the types of people were 
suing said new york lawyer theodore eppenstein who 
unsuccessfully argued the supreme court case involving arbitration 
contracts 
last week the selfregulatory bodies agreed to study a proposal 
by the securities industry association wall streets main trade 
group to remove arbitration from industry auspices to an 
independent forum such as the american arbitration association 
stock exchange officials defend the current system and see no 
need to replace it even though arbitration programs are costly 
for example the nasd said it spent 709 million on arbitration in 
198788 recovering just 134 million in fees 
arbitrations backers say that adding written opinions and 
appeals will make arbitration resemble litigation more expensive 
and drawnout for everyone defeating the purpose lawyers they 
say prefer court because they can make more money 
it probably gets down to economics said edward w morris 
jr the nyses arbitration director legal fees are less in 
arbitration 
exchange officials maintain that industry panelists are tougher 
on their counterparts because they are concerned about preserving 
ethical standards having an expert also helps decipher complex 
cases they say 
the people who serve on these panels do so because they 
feel very strongly about the integrity of the industry said 
scott noah assistant general counsel for the american stock 
exchange 
pete peterson would disagree the investor claims the 
arbitrators hearing his case laughed and talked during testimony by 
one witness hearing transcripts show one panel member told 
peterson he did not like his personality and another asked why he 
was so foolish to trust his broker 
peterson claims the broker embarked on a toorisky strategy and 
ignored repeated instructions to bail out and cut his losses 
bruce collins an attorney for the brokerage rauscher pierce 
refsnes inc said peterson was a savvy investor who agreed to the 
transactions and simply took a beating the firm denies wrongdoing 
collins claimed peterson who has hired a public relations 
firm written protests to the nyse congress and the sec and paid 
for an outside study of his case is challenging the arbitration 
panel because he fears he will lose 
merits aside the peterson case shows that investors unhappy 
with arbitration do not have alternatives some lawyers say the 
lack of choice and flaws in the process subvert investor protection 
intended by depressionera securities laws 
stockbrokers say trust us with your money youre in good 
hands with us said william f davis a los angeles lawyer 
then when you lose it they say thats the breaks 
</TEXT>
