<TEXT>
not far from the site where david 
fought goliath archaeologists are peeling the mystery away from a 
vast industrial complex in a network of artificial caves dating 
back at least 2700 years 
maresha the likely birthplace of king herod flourished as a 
commercial center of about 5000 people said archaeologist amos 
kloner unique among the ancient cities mareshites established 
their industry underground they raised pigeons manufactured olive 
oil stabled horses collected rainwater and buried their dead in 
underground chambers chiseled from soft chalk limestone 
kloner who has spent 15 years excavating and mapping the 
network of more than 1000 interlocking chambers said the caves 
were in continuous use from at least the 8th century bc until 40 
bc when maresha was overrun by parthians from ancient armenia 
why they invested so heavily in underground development is still a 
puzzle especially since there are no natural caves in the region 
kloner of the state antiquities authority suggests the reason 
may have been simple practicality 
the caves were apparently created when the ancients quarried 
stones to build a hilltop fortress and surrounding houses he said 
maybe it was easier to use such chambers since the walls and roof 
were already in place 
the lifestyle especially during the pagan hellenistic period 
when maresha reached its peak a few centuries bc is becoming 
clearer 
teams have unearthed a fortress tower ordinary houses 
thousands of pottery vessels figurines a horde of silver coins 
and an almost perfectly preserved olive oil factory as far as 
the hellenistic period is concerned there is no site more 
important kloner said 
particularly important are silver coins the newest of which 
were dated 112 bc and found in a house above one of the cave 
systems kloner said the date confirmed jewish sources about the 
conquest of the city by john hyrcanus i who forced the edomites to 
convert to judaism 
pointing to an inscription found in a series of gabled burial 
chambers kloner translated the greek the bones of beretanu and 
appolonius the sons of antipater a later antipater was the 
father of herod the great and the name in maresha may be further 
proof of herods origins here he said 
most figurines and other remains in the burial chamber were 
looted during the 1970s in addition to the theft problem the 
caves are dangerous and are officially closed to the public the 
hilly terrain is punctured with open pits from collapsed chambers 
some concealed by overgrowth the caves have no lights and in 
recent years three spelunkers have been killed and a dozen injured 
the jewish national fund plans to open the site to the public by 
next year after the government spends about 1 million to make the 
site safe 
the caves in the judean foothills 30 miles southwest of 
jerusalem are along a highway built on a roman road that passes 
crusader ruins and the grassy fields of shephela where david the 
israelite defeated the philistine champion goliath that 
confrontation was about the same time maresha is first mentioned as 
an inheritance of the tribe of judah in the bible joshua 1544 
the most visually stunning finds are the olive oil works where 
giant stone crushers weights and storage chambers are virtually 
undamaged the only things missing are the giant wooden beams used 
to squeeze the olive mash the oil was drained along channels cut 
in the floor to a collection pit that could store 5000 gallons 
there are about 70 such factories in the caves and kloner 
estimated nearly half the oil used for heating and lamps was 
exported 
another cave contains 1900 holes the size and shape of modern 
loaves of bread and which housed thousands of pigeons in fact 
some contemporary birds have sneaked in and can be heard cooing 
underneath are 2yardhigh trenches kloner said were used to 
collect the droppings for fertilizing crops 
even today pigeon manure is considered by farmers to be the 
best he said adding that pigeons were also raised for meat and 
exported 
</TEXT>
