<TEXT>
as campeau corp gradually lost its footing last 
year a unique group of financial middlemen that helps keep 
department store shelves stocked demonstrated the powerful role it 
plays in retailing 
these middlemen known as factors told several apparel 
manufacturers they wouldnt step in to accept the credit risk of 
allied stores corp and federated department stores inc campeaus 
american retailing arms 
the snub didnt push allied and federated over the brink and 
into bankruptcy court but by raising the prospect of bare shelves 
the move by factors may have nudged the campeau divisions in that 
direction 
without the faith of the factoring and credit community the 
nine allied and federated chains from new yorkbased bloomingdales 
to the bon marche in seattle were in danger of losing face in the 
industry 
factoring companies have significant power in the apparel 
industry which supplies merchandise that accounts for the bulk of 
sales at many department stores their relationship with 
manufacturers is closer than that between traditional credit rating 
agencies or bill collectors and clients 
like credit agencies factors advise clothing makers whether 
its wise to deal with a particular retailer but in addition 
factors assume the credit risk of retailers for manufacturers and 
advance loans to apparel makers as well as performing much of 
their bookkeepping work 
to a certain extent were a special breed said francis x 
basile chairman and chief executive officer of the countrys 
largest factoring company cit groupfactoring inc a subsidiary 
of manufacturers hanover corp and japans daiichi kangyo bank ltd 
factoring is a long established but little understood 
occupation the practice probably goes back to antiquity but its 
modern evolution in this country began in colonial times when 
agents known as factors were hired to service mills in england 
and europe 
it started as a service at the wholesale end of the distribution 
chain involving fabrics sold by textile mills to manufacturers 
and evolved to include goods sold by manufacturers to retailers 
a factor buys a manufacturers accounts receivables and assumes 
the risks that those bills will be paid if a retailer doesnt come 
through with the money for an order of womens dresses for 
instance a factor still has to pay its client the dress maker 
the factoring fee averages about 1 percent of the volume of the 
receivables 
factors play a key role in the garment trade because the 
industry is dominated by small to mediumsized companies that cant 
afford to assume credit risks themselves 
because theyre putting their money on the line factors dont 
want their clients to accept orders from shaky retailers but 
factors cant be too conservative their clients need to sell and 
could find others more eager for their business 
basile said he tells his staff be liberal but dont get 
stuck 
factors also will allow clients to draw advances against the 
receivables giving them cash to manufacture pending orders 
factors charge interest on advances outstanding 
the wellrun the intelligent factor is going to tailormake 
an arrangement for its clients or potential clients basile said 
the uniqueness of what we do allows us some latitude in 
structuring deals and helping clients 
factoring companies also perform all the bookkeeping tasks for 
some of their clients essentially becoming a clients credit 
department 
factoring has had an image problem and some outsiders confuse 
them with lenders who charge excessive interest 
basile who has been in factoring and commercial finance for 
more than 30 years said when he was new to the business he was 
told that companies that used factors were a step away from 
bankruptcy a notion he rejects 
the fact of the matter is we have among our clients 
companies that are the rock of gibralter financially he said 
still some companies prefer not to disclose that they use 
factors making it impossible to gauge how much merchandise in 
stores is factored industry estimates range as high as 70 percent 
the volume of receivables factored in the apparel industry was 
nearly 45 billion in 1988 according to figures compiled by the 
textile and apparel trade publication daily news record 
although largely confined to the textile and apparel trades 
factors are active in footwear and home furnishings the trust 
company bank in atlanta also handles factoring in seafood and 
trucking 
we have tried to spread our tentacles theres no reason why 
many businesses cant be factored basile said i think that we 
have trouble getting into certain businesses because we have an 
undeserved reputation 
factors once were small independent outfits until banks started 
acquiring them basile said a factor doing 25 billion in annual 
volume was a giant in 1980 cits volume last year was about 75 
billion 
some banks in recent years have withdrawn from factoring and 
sold out to others in the past 10 years the number of factors has 
been halved with about 15 to 18 left 
</TEXT>
