<TEXT>
fbi raids in 15 states targeted producers of 
counterfeit automotive parts which automakers say cost them 
millions of dollars and may pose safety threats 
no indictments have been issued and no arrests have been made 
fbi spokesman john anthony said thursday he said agents were 
tallying the number and value of the confiscated parts expected to 
be in the millions of dollars 
the raids came after 2 years of undercover investigation into 
counterfeit parts general motors corp said that according to a 
federal trade commission study consumers spend about 3 billion 
yearly on fake auto parts 
richard sherman general director for us sales and marketing 
in gms service parts operations said the company had found 
dangerous parts carrying the gm label including brake linings made 
of cardboard and oil filters made of rags and a perforated food can 
we have no problem with legitimate manufacturers of quality 
auto parts said kenneth myers marketing manager for ford motor 
cos parts and service division 
we have a big problem however with manufacturers and 
distributors of poor quality unsafe and defective parts who 
wrongfully try to market their products as genuine ford parts he 
