<TEXT>
french chemical giant rhonepoulenc sa has 
agreed to merge its pharmaceutical business with rorer group inc 
in the latest drug industry deal that seeks to lower research costs 
and gain global market reach 
the two companies announced thursday that rhonepoulenc would 
contribute nearly all of its worldwide pharmaceutical operations to 
rorer in exchange for 68 percent of the new companys stock the 
remaining stock would be offered to shareholders in rorer which is 
best known for its maalox antacid 
analysts estimated the deal would be worth about 3 billion 
the new company would be one of the worlds 10 biggest 
pharmaceutical companies in terms of sales and rank no 2 in 
europe the companies said 
rorer will promote our aggressive entry into the two top world 
markets the us and japan said jeanrene fourtou 
rhonepoulencs chairman and chief executive second it moves us 
into the top 10 pharmaceutical companies and offers us the 
crtitical mass to achieve our longterm expansion plans 
rorer emphasized the companies still need to arrange financing 
and the proposed merger needs to win approval from their directors 
and stockholders 
about 75 percent of rhonepoulenc is owned by the french 
government according to rorer spokesman jeff richardson 
samuel isaly a partner in mehta and isaly a stock market 
research firm described the proposed deal as an excellent 
strategic combination 
rhonepoulenc is in the top 10 in the european pharmaceutical 
market but has no direct marketing in the united states or japan 
where rorer has a modest network established 
so in a single stroke a new pharmaceutical specialty firm is 
created with reasonably strong positions in the us europe and 
japan isaly said 
the analyst said however that the firms products are not as 
complementary as their geographic markets 
rorers major drugs are cardiovascular gastroenterology 
hypersensitivity bone metabolism and plasma products 
rhonepoulenc concentrates on cardiovascular antibiotic 
antiinflammatory central nervous system and oncology drugs 
rhonepoulenc would have a majority of the seats on the new 
companys board of directors but robert e cawthorn rorers 
chairman and chief executuve would head the new company 
rorer stockholders would get a mix of cash and securities worth 
about 73 a share according to a statement from rorer 
rorer stock closed down 75 cents a share thursday at 6287 in 
new york stock exchange trading the deal was announced after the 
market closed thursday 
the announcement was expected on monday rorer said it was 
negotiating with an unidentifed firm that would acquire 68 percent 
of its stock 
the securities and exchange commission on wednesday filed suit 
in us district court in new york charging three unidentified 
foreign firms and a swiss investor with trading on rorer stock 
based on inside information about the negotiations 
rhonepoulenc based in paris had an estimated 11 billion in 
1989 sales while rorer based in the philadelphia suburb of fort 
washington had sales of more than 11 billion 
as the cost of developing new drugs climbs the pharmaceutical 
industry has been undergoing a rash of mergers with companies 
seeking to gain higher revenues from worldwide markets while 
cutting research and development costs through consolidation 
last year philadelphiabased smithkline beckman corp merged 
with britains beecham group plc to form smithkline beecham and 
new yorkbased brisol myers co acquired squibb corp of 
princeton nj to form bristolmyers squibb co 
rorer officials compared the proposed deal with the merger that 
created marion merrell dow last year dow chemical co bought a 
controlling interest in marion labs inc a kansas city mo 
pharmaceutical company and combined the company with its 
pharmaceutical subsidiary merrell dow a minority interest remains 
in public hands keeping a stock exchange quote for marion merrell 
dow 
