<TEXT>
a consumer group is asking federal regulators 
to make sure this weeks major outage in atampt long distance service 
wasnt the result of profit motives getting in the way of quality 
the consumer federation of america said thursday it would ask 
the federal communications commission today to investigate what 
happened on monday why the outage lasted for nine hours and why 
atampt wasnt better prepared to handle it 
gene kimmelman the federations legislative director said he 
was concerned that atampt may be cutting corners under new fcc 
regulations that let the company earn whatever profits it can 
within a price cap formula that limits yearly price increases 
in moving to this new form of relaxed regulation with no limit 
on profits atampt may have reconfigured its network cutting corners 
on quality to try to boost its profits kimmelman said 
an american telephone and telegraph co spokesman labeled 
kimmelmans allegations utterly ridiculous 
the federations announcement came shortly after atampt said it 
will give its customers nine hours of discount calling on feb 14 
valentines day if the fcc approves 
atampt said it was trying to make amends for mondays ninehour 
outage in which millions of customers got busy signals and failed 
connections when they tried to use atampt long distance service the 
company blamed a computer software problem that spread from new 
york to more than 100 switching centers nationwide 
atampt which has about 80 million customers also said it would 
compensate its 800 service businesses and negotiate oneonone 
with all its business customers for possible additional concessions 
but the consumer group complained that atampt was offering its 
discounts averaging 33 percent on valentines day between 8 
am and 5 pm that mainly would benefit business the federation 
said claiming that most residential customers do their long 
distance calling during evening and nighttime hours 
in a letter being delivered today kimmelman asked the fcc to 
investigate the outage or review the monitoring standards that were 
adopted when price caps went into effect in july 
we find it difficult to understand how the network breakdown 
whatever its initial cause could have spread so far and resulted 
in so much of atampts service being disrupted for so long 
kimmelman wrote 
atampt spokesman herb linnen said the consumer groups claims were 
ridiculous and noted his companys longstanding commitment to 
quality service over more than a century 
he disputed kimmelmans statement that residential customers 
make most long distance calls in the evenings and at night 
the bulk of all long distance calls are made by residential 
customers regardless of time of day and therefore lower 
daytime prices benefit both residential and business customers 
linnen said 
atampt chairman robert e allen said his company was offering the 
valentines day discounts as a gesture to underscore how much we 
value our relationship with our customers knowing there is no way 
to make up for the inconvenience they may have experienced 
if the fcc approves atampts request the companys residential 
business and international customers would be charged an average 33 
percent less than regular weekday charges on outofstate 
directdialed calls placed during the day 
atampt which carries 70 percent of the nations longdistance 
calls said a 10minute directdialed coasttocoast call between 
8 am and 5 pm on valentines day would cost 158 compared 
with 250 on a normal weekday 
the discounts also will apply to credit card calls and 800 
service calls but not to operatorassisted calls or to calls 
placed before 8 am or after 5 pm which already are discounted 
linnen said 
the company said 800 service customers will be eligible to 
receive a credit on their bills up to the monthly service charge 
