<TEXT>
three men have been accused of breaking 
into a government computer and obtaining a classified military 
secret an act a federal prosecutor says shows the nations defense 
computers are vulnerable 
the three silicon valley computer workers kevin l poulsen 24 
mark k lottor 25 and robert e gilligan 31 are accused of 
using personal computers stolen pacific bell telephone co 
equipment and stolen access codes to tap into government and 
telephone computer computers and obtain classified military 
documents and fbi information on associates of the late philippine 
president ferdinand marcos 
peter g neumann a computer security expert at sri 
international a computer consulting company said this was the 
first case he knew of in which classified information was allegedly 
obtained by computer breakins 
the federal indictment unsealed wednesday in us district 
court in san jose is one of the first in the nation to use federal 
criminal statutes directed at computer crime assistant us 
attorney robert k crowe said on thursday 
us attorney joseph russoniello said at a news conference in 
san francisco thursday that the military secret which concerned a 
military exercise at fort bragg nc was classified at the time 
it was stolen in 1987 or 1988 but has since been declassified 
the act does signal a vulnerability in the defense system 
computers he said 
all three men are current or former employees of sun 
microsystems in mountain view or of sri international in menlo park 
according to the indictment poulsen used common burglary tools 
including surgical gloves powdered graphite and lock picks and 
forged a pacific bell employee card to steal the telecommunications 
equipment and access codes from offices in san francisco and san 
ramon in contra costa county 
poulsen and lottor ran part of the alleged conspiracy from the 
menlo park apartment they once shared crowe said 
gilligan and poulsen are accused of trafficking in codes that 
allow access to us government computers through electronic mail 
the 15page indictment said 
the charges said the computer entered by two of the men was the 
army masnet computer network used exclusively by the government 
the charges do not indicate the uses of the computer 
poulsen also is charged with burglarizing pacific bell sites to 
steal the access codes and with manufacturing fake identification 
badges to gain private computer information 
the indictment also accuses poulsen of using his computer 
knowledge to obstruct the investigation into his alleged activities 
gilligan who reportedly still works for sun and lottor who 
works for sri are expected to surrender voluntarily poulsen a 
former employee of both companies remained at large 
if convicted lottor and gilligan face up to 20 years in prison 
and fines of 30000 poulsen could be sentenced to 37 years in 
prison and a 50000 fine 
the indictment does not indicate when authorities began 
investigating the three or what the men intended to do with the 
military secrets 
