<TEXT>
the st lawrence seaway handled a record 15 
million metric tons of export steel in 1989 but total cargo tonnage 
declined 34 million metric tons due largely to a drop in canadian 
grain shipments according to preliminary yearend statistics 
the seaway handled 422 percent more export steel this year 
than it did last year said james l emery administrator of the 
saint lawrence seaway development corp which operates the us 
portion of the inland waterway 
in 1988 287000 metric tons of export steel traversed the 
waterway which runs from the atlantic ocean through the great 
lakes to duluth minn the previous record year for export steel 
through the seaway was 1982 when 125 million metric tons were 
moved 
seventy percent of us steel production is in the great lakes 
region and obviously the seaway has been increasing its share of 
that steel emery said in a statement thursday 
nationally us steel exports are estimated to have reached 36 
million metric tons in 1989 double 1988s total according to the 
american iron and steel institute 
the institute attributed the jump in us steel exports to the 
low value of the dollar an improvement in steel quality intense 
marketing of us steel in europe and the far east and improved 
productivity 
stone and salt were also shipped through the seaway in record 
amounts stone was up 4 percent from 432000 metric tons in 1988 
to 448000 metric tons salt increased 34 percent from one million 
metric tons in 1988 to 13 million metric tons 
on the downside canadian grain shipments through the seaway 
dropped 42 million metric tons last year according to the seaway 
corporation 
other declines were seen in fuel oil which dropped 35 percent 
chemicals down 22 percent coke down 13 percent and scrap iron 
and steel 14 percent 
as a result total seaway tonnage dropped to 371 million metric 
tons a 9 percent decline from 1988s total of 405 million metric 
tons 
while all these figures were preliminary emery said the final 
tonnages would vary by a few metric tons if at all when they are 
released next month 
almost 2800 commercial vessels traveled through us seaway 
locks in 1989 on average they carried cargo weighing 17292 tons 
about 2 percent more than in 1988 the corporation said 
the last vessel cleared the seaway on dec 23 and the waterway 
was closed for the winter locks are now undergoing improvements 
and winter maintenance 
