<TEXT>
state regulators are considering whether 
longdistance phone companies should be required to provide 
information about competing services when they suffer outages like 
the one that crippled atampts network on monday 
we want to make sure that a customer who wants to make a phone 
call can get the information to get a carrier to complete the 
call said george dawson a spokesman for the state board of 
public utilities 
atampts longdistance service nationwide was out for nine hours 
on monday company officials traced the problem to a bug in a new 
software program 
dawson said bpu officals had read news accounts of people who 
complained that during the outage atampt operators refused to give 
out the access codes of the nations two other major longdistance 
carriers mci and us sprint 
dawson said the board itself had received no complaints 
i dont think anybody is thinking that atampt has the 
responsibility to pick another carrier for the caller dawson 
said but he said longdistance companies and the states two local 
telephone companies new jersey bell and united telephone are 
required as public utilities to provide any telephone numbers 
requested including those of competinglongdistance companies 
new jersey has six longdistance carriers and a seventh company 
that transmits data long distance dawson said twenty companies 
package longdistance service for resale 
atampt spokesman harry baumgartner said the company was concerned 
that whatever rule the bpu proposed would equitably apply to all 
longdistance companies 
baumgartner said that more than 400 longdistance companies 
operated nationally plus another 300 alternative operator 
services its extremely difficult if not impossible to track 
all of their access codes he said 
moreover he said atampt does not want to be in the position of 
making preferential decisions in telling callers which competitor 
to call 
mondays outage struck quickly and unexpectedly and atampt did 
not have working procedures in place for its operators baumgartner 
said atampt changed procedures to allow operators to provide the 
access codes at about 6 pm 
new jersey bell operators do not give access codes but will 
provide telephone numbers for people to call to obtain the codes 
said new jersey bell spokeswoman karen johnson 
we are really prohibited from giving out carrierspecific 
information and we feel the access codes fall into that 
category ms johnson said she said many long distance companies 
did not want other companies giving out their access codes 
united telephone operators may not recommend long distance 
carriers said glenn lewis a united spokesman he said the company 
did check with its lawyers during the outage to see what 
information operators could give out 
