<TEXT>
united technologies corp on friday 
announced that the company is adopting a new ethics code governing 
the professional conduct of the company and its 185000 employees 
the announcement came a little more than a year after the 
defense giant came under scrutiny during a pentagon investigation 
into military procurement practices but a company spokesman said 
the probe had nothing to do with the new ethics policy 
in outlining the plan during a meeting friday with top 
executives that was telecast to 13 utc offices around the country 
robert f daniell utc chairman and chief executive officer said 
the code was drafted in response to increased public attention on 
corporate ethics in recent years 
utc top management and its board of directors decided that 
public expectations should be addressed by issuing a code of ethics 
which clearly states the corporations principles and established 
standards of conduct daniell said in a statement 
the pentagons procurement investigation began in the fall of 
1988 and focused on allegations that us defense officials were 
bribed for confidential contract information 
utc spokeswoman peg hashem said daniell was asked by an employee 
on friday about whether the new policy was a response to the 
investigation hashem quoting daniell as responding absolutely 
not 
he said that over the past several years we have placed a lot 
of emphasis on defenserelated issues in the ethics area and about 
midyear of 1989 top management began discussions about whether we 
shouldnt broaden our focus and come up with a comprehensive ethics 
code that we would apply across utc both for our commercial and 
aerospace side said ms hashem 
its not that we didnt have an ethics code before we did 
she said we had lots of policies addressing ethics but this was 
an effort to pull it together in a comprehensive way and well be 
applying it consistently across utc 
pratt amp whitney the jet engine division of utc became a focus 
of the probe amid allegations that a company official had obtained 
confidential contract information from general electric co a 
chief competitor for military jet engine contracts the probe 
dubbed ill wind by federal officials is ongoing a 
congressional source who insisted on anonymity said friday 
in his remarks to employees daniell said the new code spells 
out what the company can and cannot do in its worldwide 
operations 
we can and should take great pride in our reputation and we 
must commit ourselves to its continuation as the basis for our 
future success he said 
daniell also announced the formation of a new business practices 
unit to oversee the new ethics code 
the office will be made up of a network of business practices 
officers at each of the companys operating units the officers 
will be available for employees to obtain information guidance and 
interpretation relating to the ethics code 
frank w mcabee former vice presidentgovernment contracts and 
compliance has been named vice president of business practices 
and will oversee the new unit and be in charge of enforcing the new 
code 
