<TEXT>
bank of new england corp said friday it expects 
to report a 105 billion loss for 1989 and said it was actively 
pursuing the sale of more than 6 billion in assets 
the company new englands secondlargest bank holding company 
after bank of boston corp issued a statement that also said it 
expected to enter a consent order with federal regulators to 
reshape the companys operations 
analysts said a mounting pile of bad real estate loans a 
reflection of the slump throughout the region made bank of new 
england a growing target for a federal takeover 
its like do they survive time said virginia adair a 
banking analyst with drexel burnham lambert inc in new york the 
odds are increasingly slim 
bank of new englands stock tumbled after the companys 
announcement falling 137 to 287 a share in new york stock 
trading it was the days most active stock with 676 million 
shares changing hands 
the company said it expected to report a loss of approximately 
12 billion for the fourth quarter making its annual loss about 
105 billion after boosting its reserves against possible credit 
losses to 165 billion 
the company which has seen its assets shrink in the last 
quarter from around 32 billion to 29 billion said it expected to 
have 225 billion in nonperforming assets mostly troubled real 
estate loans 
standard amp poors said friday it was slightly lowering its 
credit rating for bank of new englands senior and subordinated 
debt certificates of deposit and debt issues supported by letters 
of credit 
the wall street credit rating agency said its action reflected 
the continuing deterioration of bank of new englands loan 
portfolio sampp said the companys reserves appeared adequate to 
cover currently identified problem assets 
earnings prospects however are poor given the high level of 
nonperforming assets and pricing pressure upon the companys 
financing sampp said in a news release with reduced capital 
levels the company has little financial flexibility to address any 
further deterioration in loan quality or any other problems that 
may develop 
the recent real estate slump has hurt many banks but analysts 
said bank of new england was one of the biggest victims because its 
growth was based largely on an aggressive lending strategy during a 
construction boom earlier in the 1980s 
analysts say the bank financed some loans that in retrospect 
look questionable now with the real estate market declining 
developers are having trouble making loan payments 
the bank has come under increased scrutiny by federal 
regulators last month chairman walter connolly said he was 
relinquishing his role as chief executive officer 
bank of new england said friday it expects to enter consent 
orders with the federal reserve board and the federal comptroller 
of the currency dean debuck a spokesman for the comptrollers 
office in washington dc said the order would be issued soon 
although he declined to be specific and said it would outline 
steps the bank has to take to restore its weakened condition 
the order should contain directives to raise more capital and 
improve management controls over lending he said 
but debuck said in general terms that by agreeing to sign a 
consent order a bank would not necessarily avoid a possible 
federal takeover it can go either way he said if it can 
raise capital then it strengthens the bank if it cant raise 
capital then it doesnt strengthen the bank 
the bank has been trying to raise money through the sale of 
assets earlier this week federal regulators reportedly rejected a 
tentative agreement for bank of new england to sell some 
subsidiaries to fleetnorstar financial group inc in providence 
ri 
analysts say the bank would have a hard time finding another 
bank or investor to take over the company and the federal 
government would not likely approve the sale of its stronger 
subsidiaries because that would leave the bank in worse financial 
shape 
among the assets bank of new england is selling are 1 billion 
in leasing assets 13 billion in home equity loans and 3 billion 
in commercial loans 
to cut costs the bank said it had consolidated many operations 
resulting in the elimination of 35 million in annual expenses and 
900 staff positions through attrition sales and cutbacks 
